<div class="quotetitle">6T4 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />For example: some claim that all of the bits of the registers of mappers 2 and 3 are used for bankswitching while others say only some bits are used.<br /></div><br />Possibly because the mapper represented by the iNES mapper number has a superset of the hardware's functionality. The emulated mapper implements all bits while the actual hardware implements only some. In most of these cases, in the "variants" section on the wiki, I try to explain what would be required to implement in hardware the same extension that the iNES mapper implements.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Also, I have yet to see a single document that fully explains the CPU<br /></div><br />Have you checked 6502.org?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />particularly the unofficial opcodes.... Are they the same as on a 6502?<br /></div><br />Yes, with the possible exception of a couple unstable opcodes that produce <a href="http://visual6502.org/wiki/index.php?title=6502_Opcode_8B_%28XAA,_ANE%29" class="postlink">analog-like behavior</a>.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue May 31, 2011 4:02 am</p><hr />
